    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.6-7_0001" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">GENERAL SCHUYLER
                        <lb/>
                    BOHEMIAN CLUB
                        <lb/>
                    SAN FRANCISCO, CALIF.</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>February 3" 1920</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>To Jno. <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt Esq:</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Bancroft. Nebraska.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>My dear Sir:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I regret delay in acknowledging your letter of January 15, but I have been at a loss what to say, and I have not been able to think of it except at intervals.</p>
                
                <p>I was not present at the Rosebud fight and did not see Captain Henry wounded. I joined Gen. Crook a few days after the affair. In order to reach him I rode from Fort Fetterman with a sergeant and a civilian, 186 miles in three nights and two days, and the evening before I reached him I had a dramatic meeting with the south-bound wagon train which carried Capt. Henry and the other wounded. After joining Gen. Crook, under whom I had commanded Apache Indian Scouts in Arizona, I remained with him through the campaign, and others. Among other experiences I was with Gen Merritt in the relief of the Thornburg Expedition in 1879. I was virtually on Gen. Crook's staff for several years being actually an aide de camp for five, so that I am rather familiar with the history of that era. (except for what I have forgotten).</p>
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.6-7_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                    
                <p>My relations have long been insistent upon my writing up some of my old experiences but I never seem to find the time to become absorbed in it. The same would apply to my attempting to do it now for you. Although I should very much like to be of service to you &#8212;</p>
                
                <p>I will look up the "Three Friends" and "Hugh Glass" and see what inspiration I can get. Have you ever seen the description of the Rosebud fight written by a lieutenant named Henry <hi rend="caps">R.</hi> Lemly? He is now Capt. <hi rend="caps">NRL.</hi> (retired but on duty) Office of <hi rend="caps">Q.M.</hi> Gen'l 19th and <unclear>13</unclear> Sts. <hi rend="caps">N.W.</hi> Washington <hi rend="caps">D.C.</hi></p>
                
                <p>I will keep your letter as a reminder to give you what I can on the subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>W.S. Schuyler
                
                    Brig Gen'l U.S. Army. Retired-</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
